VALUES
(42, 10, 28, 26, 20, 21, 21, 'thou shalt live', 'Connection of Life Through Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of living through obedience to God''s commands. In Luke, the affirmation of doing right leads to life, while Ezekiel states that doing God''s statutes results in life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 28, 42, 7, 43, 43, 'Thou hast answered right', 'Judgment and Right Answers', 'This connection highlights the theme of correct judgment in both passages. In Luke 10:28, the affirmation of a right answer leads to life, while in Luke 7:43, the acknowledgment of a right judgment is similarly affirmed.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 28, 45, 3, 19, 19, 'this do, and thou shalt live', 'Connection of Law and Life', 'This connection highlights the relationship between the law and the concept of life. In Luke, the command to ''do'' the law is linked to living, while Romans emphasizes the law''s role in revealing guilt, suggesting that true life cannot be achieved through the law alone.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 42, 16, 15, 15, 'justify himself', 'Self-Justification Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of self-justification. In Luke 10:29, the question of ''who is my neighbour'' arises from a desire to justify oneself, while Luke 16:15 critiques those who justify themselves before men, highlighting the contrast with God''s knowledge of the heart.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 3, 19, 34, 34, 'who is my neighbour?', 'Love for Neighbors and Strangers', 'This connection highlights the theme of loving others, as both passages emphasize the importance of treating others with kindness and compassion. In Luke, the question of ''who is my neighbour?'' reflects the broader command in Leviticus to love the stranger as oneself.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 42, 18, 9, 11, 'willing to justify himself', 'Self-Justification and Neighbor', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-justification in both passages. The lawyer in Luke 10 seeks to justify himself, while the Pharisee in Luke 18 expresses his righteousness by comparing himself to others.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 45, 10, 3, 3, 'willing to justify himself', 'Self-Justification and Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-justification present in both passages. In Luke, the question of ''who is my neighbour'' reflects an attempt to define righteousness on one''s own terms, while Romans addresses the ignorance of God''s righteousness in favor of establishing one''s own.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 48, 3, 11, 11, 'willing to justify himself', 'Justification and Faith Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of justification in both passages. In Luke, the question of who is my neighbor reflects a desire to justify oneself, while Galatians emphasizes that justification comes through faith, not the law.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 40, 5, 43, 44, 'who is my neighbour', 'Love and Neighbor Connection', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''neighbour'' in both passages. Luke 10:29 questions the definition of ''neighbour,'' while Matthew 5:43-44 expands the idea to include loving one''s enemies, suggesting a broader understanding of who qualifies as a neighbour.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 29, 45, 4, 2, 2, 'justify himself', 'Justification and Neighbor Concept', 'This connection highlights the theme of justification in both passages. In Luke, the question of who qualifies as a neighbor reflects a desire to justify oneself, while Romans discusses justification by works versus faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 19, 88, 4, 4, 'half dead', 'Connection of Despair and Vulnerability', 'Both passages emphasize a state of being in peril and lacking strength. The man in Luke is left ''half dead,'' while the speaker in Psalms feels as one ''that hath no strength.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 42, 18, 31, 31, 'Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the journey motif present in both passages. The man going down from Jerusalem to Jericho and the disciples going up to Jerusalem both signify important transitions that lead to significant events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 24, 51, 52, 52, 'wounded him', 'Connection of Woundedness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being wounded. In Luke, the man is left half dead, while in Jeremiah, the wounded shall groan. This connection highlights the suffering experienced by individuals in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 26, 30, 24, 24, 'wounded him, and departed, leaving him half dead', 'Wounded Man Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of a wounded man, highlighting vulnerability and suffering. The SOURCE verse describes a man left half dead, while the TARGET passage speaks of groanings of a deadly wounded man.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 42, 19, 28, 28, 'went down from Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the journey motif present in both passages. The ''certain man'' descends from Jerusalem, while Jesus ascends to Jerusalem, emphasizing the significance of these locations in their respective narratives.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 30, 25, 2, 12, 12, 'wounded', 'Wounded and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being wounded and left in a state of distress. The man in Luke is left half dead, while Lamentations describes individuals swooning as the wounded in the streets.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 19, 69, 20, 20, NULL, 'Lack of Compassion in Both Passages', 'This connection highlights the theme of abandonment in both passages. In Luke 10:31, the priest''s refusal to help mirrors the lack of pity expressed in Psalms 69:20.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 62, 3, 16, 18, NULL, 'Compassion and Action in Love', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion and the necessity of action in love. In Luke 10:31, the priest''s failure to help reflects a lack of compassion, while 1 John 3:17 emphasizes that true love requires action towards those in need.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 20, 21, 13, 13, NULL, 'Response to the Cry of the Poor', 'This connection highlights the theme of neglecting those in need. Both passages emphasize the consequences of ignoring the cries of the vulnerable, as seen in the priest''s action in Luke and the warning in Proverbs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 24, 5, 31, 31, 'priest', 'Priests and Their Actions', 'This connection highlights the behavior of priests in both passages. In Luke, the priest''s indifference is mirrored by Jeremiah''s critique of priests who rule unjustly.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 28, 6, 9, 9, 'priest', 'Priests and Moral Failure', 'This connection highlights the moral failure of priests in both passages. In Luke, the priest''s inaction reflects the lewdness and consent to wrongdoing described in Hosea.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 8, 2, 3, 3, NULL, 'Chance Encounters in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of unexpected encounters. In Luke, the priest''s choice to pass by contrasts with Ruth''s ''hap'' of finding Boaz''s field, suggesting the significance of divine providence in seemingly random events.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 31, 19, 142, 4, 4, NULL, 'Isolation and Lack of Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of abandonment and neglect. In both passages, there is a sense of being overlooked, as the priest ''passed by on the other side'' and the speaker in Psalms finds that ''no man cared for my soul.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 32, 20, 27, 10, 10, 'passed by on the other side', 'Compassion and Proximity', 'This connection highlights the importance of being present for others in times of need. Both passages emphasize the value of a neighbor who is near, contrasting with those who pass by without offering help.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 32, 44, 18, 17, 17, NULL, 'Indifference to Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of indifference in both passages. In Luke, the Levite''s choice to pass by reflects a lack of compassion, while in Acts, Gallio''s disregard for the beating of Sosthenes shows a similar apathy towards injustice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 32, 19, 109, 25, 25, NULL, 'Reproach and Indifference', 'This connection highlights the theme of being looked upon with disdain. In both passages, the act of looking signifies a lack of compassion or empathy, as the Levite passes by and the speaker in Psalms experiences reproach.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 32, 55, 3, 2, 2, 'passed by on the other side', 'Selfishness and Indifference', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-centeredness. In Luke 10:32, the Levite''s choice to pass by reflects a lack of compassion, paralleling the unthankful and unholy attitudes described in 2 Timothy 3:2.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 33, 11, 8, 50, 50, 'had compassion on him', 'Compassion in Human Relationships', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion in both passages. In Luke, the Samaritan''s compassion is a direct response to human suffering, while in 1 Kings, the plea for compassion emphasizes the need for mercy among captors and the captive.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 33, 24, 38, 7, 13, 'had compassion on him', 'Compassion in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion as both the Samaritan and Ebed-melech demonstrate care for those in distress. Both figures take action to help individuals in dire situations, showcasing a moral imperative to assist others.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 33, 42, 7, 13, 13, 'had compassion on him', 'Compassion in Healing Contexts', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of compassion in moments of need. In Luke 10:33, the Samaritan shows compassion to a wounded man, while in Luke 7:13, Jesus expresses compassion to a grieving woman.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
